Part 1: Data Analysis

A researcher wants to understand the effects of daily stressors, social interaction, and year of undergraduate study on stress levels in undergraduate programs at University of Tatooine. To investigate this, they recruited 150 undergraduate students from the university. Each participant was first asked which year of undergraduate study they were from (freshman or senior). Each participant was then asked how bad their day was and to rate it from 1 (not bad at all) to 5 (terrible). Then, each participant was asked how much social interaction they have been having (on average in a given day) and to rate it from 1 (not at all) to 5 (a lot). Finally, each participant was asked to self-report the levels of stress they have been experiencing in the last one month on a scale of 1 (no stress at all) to 51 (extremely so). The researcher predict that the interaction effect of having a bad day, the amount of social interaction, and year of undergraduate study will significantly predict stress levels, such that the impact of a bad day on stress will differ based on both the amount of social interaction and whether the participant is a freshman or senior. The codebook for the dataset is below. Codebook for the âhw_16_data.csvâ

peta <- function(compact, augmented) {
  sse_c <- sum(residuals(compact)^2)
  sse_a <- sum(residuals(augmented)^2)
  
  (sse_c - sse_a)/sse_c
}

2. Test the appropriate model for the researchersâ original hypothesis. Suppose you were testing the effect of âclassâ, âbad_dayâ, and âtalkâ and their interaction on the âstressâ reported by the undergraduate participants. Write out what your equation would look like and describe which coefficients correspond to the various main effects and the interaction effects.Run the model.Generate F-statistics for each predictor. Generate partial eta-squared values for each predictor. Generate 95% confidence intervals for each predictor

stress=Î²0 + Î²1 * class+ Î²2 * bad_day+Î²3 * talk+ Î²4 * (classÃbad_day)+ Î²5 * (classÃtalk)+ Î²6 * (bad_dayÃtalk) + Î²7 * (classÃbad_dayÃtalk) + Ïµ

Î²0 is the intercept (the baseline stress level for freshmen with no bad day and no social interaction), Î²1 is the coefficient for the class variable (the difference in stress between freshmen and seniors), Î²2 is the coefficient for bad_day (the effect of having a bad day on stress), Î²3 is the coefficient for talk (the effect of social interaction on stress), Î²4, Î²5, and Î²6 represent the interactions between the variables, Î²7 represents the three-way interaction effect of class, bad_day, and talk on stress, Ïµ is the error term.

The study aimed to investigate the effects of undergraduate year level (class), daily stressors (bad day), and social interaction (talk) on stress levels reported by students at the university. Specifically, the researchers hypothesized that the interaction of these variables would significantly predict stress, such that the impact of a bad day on stress would differ based on both the amount of social interaction and whether the participant was a freshman or senior. To test this hypothesis, two models were fit: a full model that included the three-way interaction, and a more compact model that included only the main effects and key interactions.

Full Model Results: The full model included the main effects of class, bad_day, and talk, as well as their two-way and three-way interactions. The results of the linear model are summarized here:

Class (Freshman vs.Â Senior):

b = 0.1035, SE = 5.7548, t = 0.018, p = 0.9857 This suggests no significant difference in stress between freshmen and seniors. 95% CI: [-11.27, 11.48]

Bad Day:

b = 2.4029, SE = 1.1284, t = 2.129, p = 0.0349 The effect of having a bad day on stress is significant, with each bad day increasing reported stress by about 2.4 units. 95% CI: [0.17, 4.63]

Talk (Social Interaction):

b = 4.4668, SE = 1.8595, t = 2.402, p = 0.0176 More social interaction significantly reduces stress, with each increase in the talk variable decreasing stress by about 4.47 units. 95% CI: [0.79, 8.14]

Class Ã Bad Day Interaction:

b = 0.1244, SE = 2.0069, t = 0.062, p = 0.9507 The interaction between class and bad day is not significant. 95% CI: [-3.84, 4.09]

Class Ã Talk Interaction:

b = -1.9797, SE = 2.2823, t = -0.867, p = 0.3872 The interaction between class and talk is not significant. 95% CI: [-6.49, 2.53]

Bad Day Ã Talk Interaction:

b = 0.1041, SE = 0.5744, t = 0.181, p = 0.8565 The interaction between bad day and talk is not significant. 95% CI: [-1.03, 1.24]

Class Ã Bad Day Ã Talk Interaction:

b = -1.5260, SE = 0.7336, t = -2.080, p = 0.0393 The three-way interaction between class, bad day, and talk is significant. This suggests that the impact of bad days on stress is moderated by both class and the level of social interaction. 95% CI: [-2.98, -0.08]

Model Fit:

F-statistic = 74.72, df = 7, 142, p-value < 2.2e-16 R-squared = 0.7865, Adjusted R-squared = 0.776 Compact Model Results: The compact model included the main effects of class, bad_day, and talk, and the interaction between class and bad_day. The results are summarized here:

Class (Freshman vs.Â Senior):

b = 0.1437, SE = 2.3688, t = 0.061, p = 0.9517 No significant effect of class on stress. 95% CI: [-4.54, 4.83] Bad Day:

b = 2.8742, SE = 0.5058, t = 5.683, p < 2e-16 Significant positive effect of bad day on stress. 95% CI: [1.87, 3.87] Talk (Social Interaction):

b = 1.4575, SE = 0.5054, t = 2.884, p = 0.00453 Significant negative effect of social interaction on stress. 95% CI: [0.46, 2.46] Class Ã Bad Day Interaction:

b = -5.8911, SE = 0.7161, t = -8.227, p < 2e-16 The interaction between class and bad day is significant, with the effect of a bad day on stress being stronger for seniors than for freshmen. 95% CI: [-7.31, -4.48] Model Fit:

F-statistic = 84.42, df = 4, 145, p-value < 2.2e-16 R-squared = 0.6996, Adjusted R-squared = 0.6913 Hypothesis Testing: The researchersâ hypothesis was partially confirmed. While the three-way interaction between class, bad_day, and talk was significant in the full model, the interaction between class and bad day was the most meaningful in the compact model. This suggests that the impact of a bad day on stress indeed differs by year level (class), but the role of social interaction (talk) was less clearly moderated. Social interaction had a significant negative effect on stress in both models, but the three-way interaction with class and bad day was less informative in the compact model.

Effect Sizes: Partial Eta-Squared (Full Model): 0.2892676, indicating a medium to large effect size for the predictors and interactions in the full model.
